Q) You are given two integer arrays nums 1 and nums2 of size n.
You can perform the following two operations any number of times on these two arrays:
• Swap within the same array: Choose two indices i and j. Then, choose either to swap and nums1 [jl, or nums2[i] and nums2 [jl). This operation is free of charge.
nums1 [i]
• Swap between two arrays: Choose an index i). Then, swap nums1 [il and [nums2 [i]. This operation
incurs a cost of 1.
Return an integer denoting the minimum cost to make (nums1) and
nums2) identical. If this is not possible,
return -1.
Example 1:
Input: nums1 = [10,20], nums2 = [20,10]
Output: 0
Explanation:
• Swap |nums2[0] = 20 and |nums2[1] = 10.
• nums2) becomes [10, 20]).
• This operation is free of charge.
nums1 and (nums2) are now identical. The cost is O.

Solution:
class Solution {
    public int minCost(int[] nums1, int[] nums2) {
        HashMap<Integer,Integer> freq = new HashMap<>();
        for(int i:nums1)
            freq.put(i,freq.getOrDefault(i,0)+1);
        for(int i:nums2)
            freq.put(i,freq.getOrDefault(i,0)+1);
        for(int v : freq.values()){
            if(v % 2 != 0) 
                return -1;
        }
        HashMap<Integer,Integer> f1 = new HashMap<>();
        for(int x : nums1)
            f1.put(x, f1.getOrDefault(x,0)+1);
        int ans = 0;
        for(int v:f1.keySet()){
            int t = freq.get(v)/2;
            int h = f1.get(v);
            if(h>t)
                ans+= (h-t);
        }
        return ans;
    }
}
